`scrollbar-width` is a CSS property that is used to control the width of the scrollbar. This property can take one of three values: `auto`, `thin`, or `none`.

- `auto`: The browser determines the optimal width for the scrollbar based on the content of the element.
- `thin`: The scrollbar is set to a thin width.
- `none`: The scrollbar is not displayed.

Here's an example of how you could use `scrollbar-width` to set the width of the scrollbar to `thin`:

```css
/* Set the width of the scrollbar to 'thin' */
::-webkit-scrollbar {
  scrollbar-width: thin;
}

/* Set the width of the scrollbar to 'thin' for Firefox*/
scrollbar-width: thin;
```

It's worth noting that `scrollbar-width` is a relatively new CSS property and may not be supported in all older browsers. Additionally, it may be overridden by other scrollbar-related properties depending on the browser. 

